      <body>
         <head type="date">
            <date when="1803-11-11">November 11, 1803</date>
         </head>
         <div type="entry" xml:id="lc.jrn.1803-11-11.01" n="lc.geo.1803-11-11.01">
            <sp who="ml">
               <speaker>Lewis</speaker>
               <ab>
                  <date>11th November—<ref target="n02111101" n="1"/>
                  </date>
               </ab>
               <p>
Arrived as <name type="place" key="Fort Massac (Ill.)">Massac</name>
                  <ref target="n02111102" n="2"/>    engaged <name type="person" key="Drouillard, George">George Drewyer</name>
                  <ref target="n02111103" n="3"/> in the public service as an Indian Interpretter, contracted to pay him 25 dollards pr. month for his services.—    <name type="person" key="Swan, William">Mr Swan</name>
                  <ref target="n02111104" n="4"/> Assistant Millitary agent at that place advanced him <hi rend="italic">thirty</hi> dollars on account of his pay.—

</p>
            </sp>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="notes">
            <note xml:id="n02111101" n="1">
               <name type="person" key="Lewis, Meriwether">Lewis</name> has written 11 over 12 for the date and continued to make corrections through November 17. He must have discovered his error about November 18. There is a blank half page at the end of this entry and a considerable amount of unused space on the pages during the next week or so of journalizing.</note>
            <note xml:id="n02111102" n="2">The fort site, on a promontory just above <name type="place" key="Metropolis, Ill.">Metropolis</name>, <name type="place" key="Massac County, Ill.">Massac County</name>, <name type="place" key="Illinois">Illinois</name>, commands a strategic view of the <name type="place" key="Ohio River">Ohio River</name>. Established by the French in 1757, ceded to the British in 1763, and abandoned the next year, it was soon destroyed by <name type="native_nation" key="Chickasaw Indians">Chickasaw Indians</name>. The ruins were not restored until 1794 by Americans under orders from <name type="person" key="Wayne, Anthony">General Anthony Wayne</name>. It was again abandoned as a military post after the War of 1812. Thwaites (EWT), 4:276–77; <hi rend="italic">Illinois Guide,</hi> 433–34; Fortier, 57–71.</note>
            <note xml:id="n02111103" n="3">
               <name type="person" key="Drouillard, George">George Drouillard</name>, whose name neither <name type="person" key="Lewis, Meriwether">Lewis</name> nor <name type="person" key="Clark, William">Clark</name> ever managed to spell right, became one of the most valuable members of the expedition. See <ref n="v02.appendix.a" type="related">Appendix A</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="n02111104" n="4">
               <name type="person" key="Swan, William">William Swan</name> of <name type="place" key="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</name>, stationed at <name type="place" key="Fort Massac (Ill.)">Fort Massac</name> from 1802 to 1804, was in charge of financial affairs at the post. Quaife (MLJO), 47 n. 4.</note>
         </div>
